    <div class="content-container">
      <div class="section" id="orientation-main">
        <h2>I. ORIENTATION <span class="source-tag">COMPASS</span></h2>

        <!-- PART A -->
        <div id="what-system-does">
          <h3>A. What This System Does</h3>
          <p>This is a <strong>spatial navigation system</strong> for story analysis. It treats every story as a mappable territory with two primary dimensions:</p>

          <div class="dimension-horizontal">
            <h4>HORIZONTAL AXIS (Story Timeline Position):</h4>
            <p>Where you are in the narrative's temporal/structural progression. Think of this as the <em>timeline</em> - but measured through multiple overlapping systems simultaneously (clock positions, acts, beats, runtime, symmetry points).</p>
            <p style="margin-top: 15px;"><strong>Systems and frameworks</strong> (from the <a class="cross-link" href="#">Narrative Cognition Map</a>) relevant to HORIZONTAL DIMENSION (Story Timeline Position):</p>
            <ul>
              <li><a class="cross-link" href="#">Hero's Journey</a> (Campbell/Vogler) - Stages and thresholds</li>
              <li><a class="cross-link" href="#">Story Circle</a> (Dan Harmon) - 8-point cyclical structure</li>
              <li><a class="cross-link" href="#">Act Structure Systems</a> - 3-act, 4-act, 5-act frameworks</li>
              <li><a class="cross-link" href="#">Beat Systems</a> - Save the Cat, Story Grid markers</li>
              <li><a class="cross-link" href="#">Narrative Geometry</a> - Chiastic, Ring, Mirroring structures</li>
              <li><a class="cross-link" href="#">Classical Dramatic Structure</a> - Freytag's Pyramid</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <hr style="margin: 32px 0; border: none; border-top: 2px solid #E0E0E0;"/>

          <div class="dimension-vertical">
            <h4>VERTICAL AXIS (Story Depth Dimension):</h4>
            <p>Dimension of examined meaning. Story operates on multiple simultaneous strata - from surface-level observable phenomena to deep archetypal/mythic structures.</p>
            <p style="margin-top: 15px;"><strong>Systems and frameworks</strong> (from the <a class="cross-link" href="#">Narrative Cognition Map</a>) relevant to VERTICAL Axis (Story Depth Dimension):</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Surface Dimension 5:</strong> Semiotics, Visual Symbolism, Aesthetic Frameworks, Surface Expression</li>
              <li><strong>Structural Dimension 4:</strong> Dramatica, Plot Mechanics, Genre Conventions, Functional Dynamics</li>
              <li><strong>Cognitive Dimension 3:</strong> Logical Fallacies, Rhetorical Modes, Thought Patterns, Belief and Reasoning Structures</li>
              <li><strong>Psychological Dimension 2:</strong> Jung, Enneagram, Character Interiority, Defense Mechanisms, Wounds &amp; Desires, Emotion</li>
              <li><strong>Archetype Dimension 1:</strong> Jungian Archetypes, Universal Myths, Collective Unconscious, Primordial Patterns</li>
              <li><strong>Core Dimension 0:</strong> Central Problem/Argument, Moral Premise, Story Question, Essential Truth, Main Philosophical Conflict, Central Theme</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <!-- Tabs: Notation / Reading / Examples -->
          <Tabs
            id="orientation-coords"
            accent="blue"
            labels={["Notation", "Reading", "Examples"]}
          >
            <div slot="tab-0">
              <h4>Coordinate Notation</h4>
              <p>Any point in your analysis can be located using coordinates:</p>
              <p style="margin-top: 8px;"><code>[Story Timeline Position] / [Story Depth Dimension]</code></p>
              <h4 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Terminology</h4>
              <p><strong>VERTICAL AXIS: Story Depth Dimension</strong></p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Dimension</strong> for depth (Dimension 5-0, descending from surface to core)</li>
                <li>These are analytical strata or depths</li>
              </ul>
              <p style="margin-top: 12px;"><strong>HORIZONTAL AXIS: Story Timeline Position</strong></p>
              <ul>
                <li>Use <strong>Position</strong> for story location</li>
                <li>These are temporal coordinates or narrative stations</li>
              </ul>
              <p style="margin-top: 12px;"><strong>Notation becomes:</strong></p>
              <ul>
                <li><code>[Story Timeline Position] / [Story Depth Dimension]</code></li>
                <li>→ <code>[12:00] / [Dimension 3]</code></li>
                <li>Read as: "Position twelve o'clock, Dimension 3 (cognitive)"</li>
              </ul>
            </div>

            <div slot="tab-1">
              <h4>Reading a Coordinate</h4>
              <p>When you locate a coordinate like <code>[6:00 / Psychological Dimension 2]</code>, you're asking:</p>
              <p style="margin-left: 24px; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.75rem;">"What does Psychological Dimension 2 analysis (psychological frameworks: Jung, Enneagram, Defense Mechanisms, etc.) reveal about what's happening at Position 6:00 (which Horizontal frameworks tell us is: Midpoint, Find Point, Meet the Goddess, Maximum Vulnerability)?"</p>
              <p style="margin-top: 0.75rem;"><strong>You apply BOTH axis frameworks simultaneously at the intersection.</strong></p>
              <h4 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Format</h4>
              <p><code>[Story Timeline Position] / [Story Depth Dimension]</code> → What to examine</p>
            </div>

            <div slot="tab-2">
              <h4>Example Coordinates</h4>
              <ul style="margin-top: 10px;">
                <li><code>12:00 / Surface Dimension 5</code> → Status quo as presented (visual, dialogue, setting)</li>
                <li><code>3:00 / Structural Dimension 4</code> → Structural threshold function (what shifts mechanically)</li>
                <li><code>6:00 / Psychological Dimension 2</code> → Psychological revelation (internal discovery)</li>
                <li><code>9:00 / Cognitive Dimension 3</code> → Cognitive crisis (thought pattern breakdown)</li>
                <li><code>12:00 / Core Dimension 0</code> → Resolution of central problem</li>
              </ul>
              <h4 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Working an Example</h4>
              <p><strong>Example:</strong> <code>6:00 / Psychological Dimension 2</code> means:</p>
              <ul style="margin-top: 10px;">
                <li><strong>Story Timeline Position:</strong> Midpoint/Find Point/Revelation moment</li>
                <li><strong>Analytical Dimension:</strong> Psychological Interior (character psyche, wounds, desire)</li>
              </ul>
              <p style="margin-top: 10px;">At this coordinate, you examine: <em>What is the character discovering about themselves? What need is being fulfilled? What vulnerability is exposed?</em></p>
            </div>
          </Tabs>

          <h4 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Purpose:</h4>
          <p>This system allows you to:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Know exactly <strong>WHERE</strong> you are in an analysis</li>
            <li>Know exactly <strong>WHAT</strong> to look for at that location</li>
            <li>Track patterns across time (horizontal movement)</li>
            <li>Track patterns across depth (vertical movement)</li>
            <li>Compare stories using the same coordinate system</li>
            <li>Navigate between multiple theoretical frameworks without losing orientation</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- PART B -->
        <div id="how-it-works">
          <h3>B. How It Works: The Distinction Between Horizontal and Vertical Axes</h3>

          <div class="callout-example">
            <p><strong>HORIZONTAL AXIS = FRAMEWORKS THAT MEASURE/DEFINE [Story Timeline Position]</strong></p>
            <p style="margin-top: 12px;"><strong>VERTICAL AXIS = FRAMEWORKS THAT MEASURE/DEFINE [Story Depth Dimension]</strong></p>
          </div>

          <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">Flip each card to see the complete framework inventory for that axis.</p>

          <div class="flip-card-strip" style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">
            <FlipCard id="orient-h-axis" accent="amber" flipDirection="horizontal">
              <div slot="front">
                <div class="eyebrow eyebrow--amber" style="font-size: 0.7rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">HORIZONTAL AXIS</div>
                <h4 style="margin: 0 0 0.5rem;">Story Timeline Position</h4>
                <p style="margin: 0 0 0.75rem; color: var(--text-2); font-size: 0.875rem;">Frameworks that measure <em>when / where</em> in the story.</p>
                <ul style="margin: 0; padding-left: 1.25rem; font-size: 0.875rem; color: var(--text-2);">
                  <li>Clock/Circle system (12-point structure)</li>
                  <li>Act structures (3-act, 4-act, 5-act)</li>
                  <li>Beat systems (Save the Cat, Story Grid)</li>
                  <li>Harmon's Story Circle (8-step cycle)</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div slot="back">
                <h4 style="margin: 0 0 0.5rem; color: var(--semantic-h);">Horizontal Axis — Full Framework List</h4>
                <p style="margin: 0 0 0.5rem; font-size: 0.8125rem; color: var(--text-2);">All about tracking WHEN/WHERE in the story:</p>
                <ul style="margin: 0; padding-left: 1.25rem; font-size: 0.8125rem; line-height: 1.7;">
                  <li>Clock/Circle system (12-point structure)</li>
                  <li>Act structures (3-act, 4-act, 5-act, 7-act)</li>
                  <li>Beat systems (Save the Cat, Story Grid, etc.)</li>
                  <li>Harmon's Story Circle (8-step cycle)</li>
                  <li>Campbell's Hero's Journey (17 stages)</li>
                  <li>Vogler's adaptation</li>
                  <li>Runtime/percentage measurement systems</li>
                  <li>Symmetry/mirroring geometry systems</li>
                  <li>Story Geometry</li>
                  <li>Story Structure</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin: 0.75rem 0 0; font-size: 0.8125rem;"><strong>Notation:</strong> <code>12:00</code>, <code>3:00</code>, <code>6:00</code>, <code>9:00</code></p>
              </div>
            </FlipCard>

            <FlipCard id="orient-v-axis" accent="teal" flipDirection="horizontal">
              <div slot="front">
                <div class="eyebrow eyebrow--teal" style="font-size: 0.7rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">VERTICAL AXIS</div>
                <h4 style="margin: 0 0 0.5rem;">Story Depth Dimension</h4>
                <p style="margin: 0 0 0.75rem; color: var(--text-2); font-size: 0.875rem;">Frameworks that measure <em>what depth</em> of analysis.</p>
                <ul style="margin: 0; padding-left: 1.25rem; font-size: 0.875rem; color: var(--text-2);">
                  <li>D5 — Surface/Expressive (Semiotics)</li>
                  <li>D4 — Structural (Dramatica, Truby)</li>
                  <li>D3 — Cognitive (Fallacies, Rhetoric)</li>
                  <li>D2 — Psychological (Jung, Enneagram)</li>
                  <li>D1 — Archetypal (ATU, Propp)</li>
                  <li>D0 — Core (Moral Premise, Theme)</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div slot="back">
                <h4 style="margin: 0 0 0.5rem; color: var(--semantic-v);">Vertical Axis — Full Framework List</h4>
                <p style="margin: 0 0 0.5rem; font-size: 0.8125rem; color: var(--text-2);">All about tracking WHAT DEPTH of analysis:</p>
                <ul style="margin: 0; padding-left: 1.25rem; font-size: 0.8125rem; line-height: 1.7;">
                  <li>Jung (psychology, archetypes, shadow)</li>
                  <li>Enneagram (9 types, motivations)</li>
                  <li>Temperaments (4 types, emotional patterns)</li>
                  <li>Dramatica (8 archetypes, quads, domains, problem/solution)</li>
                  <li>Truby (character web, moral argument)</li>
                  <li>Logical fallacies (thinking errors)</li>
                  <li>Cognitive biases (perception distortions)</li>
                  <li>Rhetoric (persuasion modes)</li>
                  <li>ATU tale-types (mythic patterns)</li>
                  <li>Propp functions (narrative roles)</li>
                  <li>Semiotics (sign systems, meaning codes)</li>
                  <li>Moral Premise (thematic argument)</li>
                  <li>Defense mechanisms (psychological protection)</li>
                  <li>Lacan (desire, symbolic order)</li>
                  <li>Spiral Dynamics (worldview systems)</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin: 0.75rem 0 0; font-size: 0.8125rem;"><strong>Notation:</strong> <code>D5</code> (surface) → <code>D0</code> (core)</p>
              </div>
            </FlipCard>
          </div>

          <h4 style="margin-top: 2rem;">At Intersections:</h4>
          <p>When you locate a coordinate like <code>[6:00 / Psychological Dimension 2]</code>, you're asking:</p>
          <p style="margin-left: 24px; font-style: italic;">"What does Psychological Dimension 2 analysis (psychological frameworks: Jung, Enneagram, Defense Mechanisms, etc.) reveal about what's happening at Position 6:00 (which Horizontal frameworks tell us is: Midpoint, Find Point, Meet the Goddess, Maximum Vulnerability)?"</p>
          <p><strong>You apply BOTH axis frameworks simultaneously at the intersection.</strong></p>

          <div class="callout-example" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">
            <h4>This Structure:</h4>
            <ol>
              <li>Defines the space (both axes clearly) with visual representation</li>
              <li>Explains navigation (how to move through it)</li>
              <li>Provides intersection logic (what happens when axes meet)</li>
              <li>References without repeating (points to supporting docs)</li>
              <li>Stays spatial/coordinate-based (not just theory rehash)</li>
              <li>Is expandable (can add complexity without breaking)</li>
            </ol>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- PART C — ACCORDION -->
        <div id="how-to-navigate">
          <h3>C. How to Navigate (Basic Protocol)</h3>

          <div class="accordion-item">
            <details id="navigate-details">
              <summary class="accordion-toggle">
                <span class="accordion-toggle__label">
                  <span class="accordion-toggle__title">Navigation Protocols</span>
                  <span class="accordion-toggle__meta">Entry strategies, movement patterns, and coordinate reading</span>
                </span>
                <span class="accordion-toggle__chevron">▾</span>
              </summary>
              <div class="accordion-body">

                <div class="callout-example">
                  <p><strong>ENTRY POINT:</strong> You can enter the analysis from any coordinate. There is no required starting position.</p>
                </div>

                <h4>Common entry strategies:</h4>
                <ol>
                  <li><strong>Surface → Core</strong> (start Expressive Surface Dimension 5, drill down)</li>
                  <li><strong>Core → Surface</strong> (start Core Dimension 0, work up)</li>
                  <li><strong>Linear Timeline</strong> (12:00 → 12:00, checking each dimension)</li>
                  <li><strong>Key Position Scan</strong> (examine all dimensions at 6:00, then all dimensions at 9:00, etc.)</li>
                  <li><strong>Single Dimension Sweep</strong> (track one dimension across the entire horizontal axis)</li>
                </ol>

                <h4>Movement Protocols:</h4>
                <p><strong>Horizontal Movement (Timeline Navigation):</strong></p>
                <ul>
                  <li><strong>Scene-by-scene progression</strong> - Linear movement through narrative order</li>
                  <li><strong>Jump to symmetry points</strong> - Using mirroring axes</li>
                  <li><strong>Follow single character timeline</strong> - Track one character's journey across positions</li>
                  <li><strong>Track motif/object across positions</strong> - Follow symbolic elements through the story</li>
                  <li><strong>Cyclical returns</strong> - Examining how story circles back to origin points</li>
                  <li><strong>Parallel timeline tracking</strong> - Following multiple narrative threads simultaneously</li>
                </ul>

                <p><strong>Vertical Movement (Depth Navigation):</strong></p>
                <ul>
                  <li><strong>Drill down</strong> (surface observation Surface Dimension 5 → deeper meaning Core Dimension 0)</li>
                  <li><strong>Zoom out</strong> (archetypal pattern Archetype Dimension 1 → how it manifests Cognitive Dimension 3 and above)</li>
                  <li><strong>Cross-dimension analysis</strong> - Track same element through multiple strata</li>
                </ul>

                <p><strong>Diagonal Movement (Combined Navigation):</strong></p>
                <ul>
                  <li><strong>Track transformation:</strong> Position + layer change simultaneously</li>
                  <li>Example: Character at <code>1:00/Psychological Dimension 2</code> (psychological need) → <code>11:00/Psychological Dimension 2</code> (psychological resolution)</li>
                  <li>Example: Tracking how <a class="cross-link" href="#">Shadow</a> evolves from <code>3:00/Archetype Dimension 1</code> (archetypal encounter) → <code>9:00/Psychological Dimension 2</code> (psychological integration)</li>
                </ul>

                <p><strong>Mirroring/Symmetry Analysis:</strong></p>
                <ul>
                  <li>Compare mirror positions at same layer</li>
                  <li>Identify parallel structure across symmetry axes</li>
                  <li>Track how beginning mirrors ending</li>
                  <li>See also: <a class="cross-link" href="#">Section V: Navigation Protocols - Mirroring Analysis</a></li>
                </ul>

                <p><strong>Thematic Tracking:</strong></p>
                <ul>
                  <li>Follow theme across positions (horizontal)</li>
                  <li>Follow theme through layers (vertical)</li>
                  <li>See also: <a class="cross-link" href="#">Section V: Navigation Protocols - Thematic Tracking</a></li>
                </ul>

                <p><strong>Character Arc Tracking:</strong></p>
                <ul>
                  <li>Map character journey through positions</li>
                  <li>Examine character at each depth layer</li>
                  <li>See also: <a class="cross-link" href="#">Section V: Navigation Protocols - Character Arc Tracking</a></li>
                </ul>

                <h4>READING A COORDINATE:</h4>
                <div class="callout-example">
                  <p><strong>Format:</strong> <code>[Story Timeline Position] / [Story Depth Dimension]</code> → What to examine</p>
                  <p style="margin-top: 15px;"><strong>Example coordinates:</strong></p>
                  <ul style="margin-top: 10px;">
                    <li><code>12:00 / Surface Dimension 5</code> → Status quo as presented (visual, dialogue, setting)</li>
                    <li><code>3:00 / Structural Dimension 4</code> → Structural threshold function (what shifts mechanically)</li>
                    <li><code>6:00 / Psychological Dimension 2</code> → Psychological revelation (internal discovery)</li>
                    <li><code>9:00 / Cognitive Dimension 3</code> → Cognitive crisis (thought pattern breakdown)</li>
                    <li><code>12:00 / Core Dimension 0</code> → Resolution of central problem</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>

              </div>
            </details>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- PART D -->
        <div id="relationship-docs">
          <h3>D. Relationship to Supporting Documents</h3>
          <p>This coordinate system is a <strong>navigation framework</strong> - it tells you WHERE to look and WHAT to look for.</p>
          <p>The supporting documents provide the <strong>detailed frameworks and terminology</strong> you apply at each coordinate.</p>

          <h4>Document Hierarchy:</h4>
          <div class="callout-example">
            <p><strong>THIS DOCUMENT (Analysis Coordinate System):</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li>Defines the spatial map</li>
              <li>Provides navigation protocols</li>
              <li>Tells you which frameworks to reference at which coordinates</li>
              <li>Does NOT repeat framework details</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="callout-example">
            <p><strong>Supporting Documents:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>"The Only Story: Universal Structure"</strong> → Story position details, clock system, structural beats</li>
              <li><strong>"Narrative Cognition Map"</strong> → Layer definitions, framework taxonomy, system relationships
                <ul>
                  <li>Includes: Story Structure &amp; Narrative Geometry</li>
                  <li>Includes: Character Systems (Jung, Dramatica, Enneagram)</li>
                  <li>Includes: Cognitive Frameworks (Fallacies, Rhetoric)</li>
                  <li>Includes: Archetypal &amp; Mythic Patterns</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li><strong>"Russian Story Analysis Protocol"</strong> (if applicable) → Scene logging methods, specific workflows, timestamp systems</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <h4>When to Reference:</h4>
          <div class="example-box">
            <p>At coordinate <code>6:00 / Psychological Dimension 2</code>, this document tells you:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>What to examine:</strong> Psychological revelation, maximum vulnerability, need fulfillment</li>
              <li><strong>Which frameworks to reference:</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Universal Structure doc → "Meet the Goddess" beat, "Find Point"</li>
                  <li>Narrative Cognition Map → <a class="cross-link" href="#">Psychological Archetypes</a> section, <a class="cross-link" href="#">Transformation Arcs</a></li>
                  <li>Character-specific systems → <a class="cross-link" href="#">Jung</a>, <a class="cross-link" href="#">Enneagram</a>, <a class="cross-link" href="#">Shadow dynamics</a></li>
                </ul>
              </li>
            </ul>
            <p style="margin-top: 10px;">You consult those documents for the detailed framework content.</p>
          </div>

          <h4>Cross-Reference Notation:</h4>
          <p>Throughout this document, you'll see:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>→ [Doc Name: Section]</strong> = consult this for detail</li>
            <li><strong>↔ [Story Position / Story Layer]</strong> = related coordinate to check</li>
            <li><strong>• [Framework Name]</strong> = apply this system here</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>

    <div style="text-align: center; margin-top: 50px; padding-top: 30px; border-top: 2px solid #e2e8f0; color: #94a3b8;">
      <p>Story Analysis Coordinate System v1.0 | Section I: ORIENTATION</p>
      <p style="font-size: 0.9em; margin-top: 10px;">A Compass for Story Analysis and Narrative Mapping</p>
    </div>
  </div>

